# Open Specy Tutorial

Welcome to the Open Specy Tutorial! You will learn a common workflow for using the Open Specy package and highlights some topics that users are often requesting a tutorial on. This file will walk you through the process of the following:

- Installation
- Running Open Specy app
- Libraries
- Reading Data
- Open Specy objects
- Visualization
- Spectral Preprocessing Parameters
- Library Matching Spectra
- Additional Resources

The Open Specy R package is the backbone of the Shiny app. The choice is yours as to which you start with, we use both on a regular basis. The tutorial will talk through the R functions you can use to programatically analyze spectra. If you are looking for a tutorial about how to use the app see this [tutorial](https://raw.githack.com/wincowgerDEV/OpenSpecy-package/main/docs/articles/app.html).

# Installation

To install the most up to date and stable Open Specy version 1.5.3.

```{r}
install.packages("OpenSpecy")
```

# Open Specy App

After installing the R package, you just need to read in the package. This will load in all the functions needed for using Open Specy.

```{r}
library(OpenSpecy)
```

The package has a built in app that you can use in addition to the [web version](https://openanalysis.org/openspecy/). This will install all current versions of the spectral libraries and Open Specy code and will pop up on your screen.

```{r}
run_app()
```

When loading Open Specy for the first time you might get a message that says: "*Library missing or incomplete: derivative, nobaseline, raw, medoid_derivative, medoid_nobaseline, model_derivative, model_nobaseline; use 'get_lib()' to download a current version*".

# Read Data

The following line of code will read in your data. Open Specy currently is able to read in the following file types:

- .spa/.spc/.asp

- .jdx/.dx/ .0

- .xyz/.csv/.tsv/.txt

- .h5

- ENVI files (.dat & .hdr)

- native Open Specy .y(a)ml, .json, or .rds

- .zip files

.zip files can either contain multiple files with individual spectra in them of the non-zip formats or it can contain a .hdr and .dat file that form an ENVI file for a spectral map. If uploading a .csv file, it is ideal to label the column with the wavenumbers ***wavenumber*** and name the column with the intensities ***intensity***.

```{r}
# Provide the file path of your data
testspectra <- read_any("data/Test Data20260617-143905.csv")
```

We can also work with test data

```{r}
# Add direct file path to dataset
data("raman_hdpe")
```

# Open Specy Objects

You will notice now that the R package reads in files into an object with class OpenSpecy. This is a class we created for high throughput spectral analysis which now also preserves spectral metadata. You can even create these from scratch if you’d like.

```{r}
# seq(n1,n2,by = n): Create a vector sequence of numbers from range n1 to n2 by intervals of n 
# runif(n = ): Generates n random numbers between the range of 0 to 1  
# file_name: name of file that will be listed in the metadata

scratch_OpenSpecy <- as_OpenSpecy(
  x = seq(, , by = ),
  spectra = data.frame(runif(n = )),
  metadata = list(file_name = )
)

```

Open Specy objects are lists with three components, ***wavenumber*** is a vector of the wavenumber values for the spectra and corresponds to the rows in ***spectra*** which is a data.table where each column is a set of spectral intensities. ***metadata*** is a data.table which holds additional information about the spectra. Each row in ***metadata*** corresponds to a column in ***spectra***.

```{r}
# Access the wavenumbers
scratch_OpenSpecy$
```

